FUEL OIL POISONING - CAMBODIA: PHNOM PENH, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
******************************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat, Dec 3, 2011
Subject: Fuel oil poisoning - Cambodia: Phnom Penh, RFI


[1]
Date: Tue 29 Nov 2011
Source: The Phnom Penh Post [edited]
http://www.phnompenhpost.com/index.php/2011112953023/National-news/fumes-fuel-faintings.html


Fumes from oil used in sewing machines caused 7 workers at a garment
factory in the capital's Russey Keo district to faint yesterday [28
Nov
2011] afternoon, a union leader and company representative said.

Hai Soveth, factory president of the Free Trade Union of Workers of
Cambodia, said 7 female workers at a facility run by Su Tong Fang
Group
Ying Kan were sent to Calmette Hospital yesterday [28 Nov 2011]
evening
after they fainted from the fumes.

About 900 workers were sent home at about 4:00 pm to avoid a repeat
of
the mass fainting incidents that hit other factories, Hai Soveth
said.

A 27-year-old woman, said she felt dizzy and weak in the knees and
that
her chest tightened before she began vomiting from the fumes.

"My health was weak and when I smelled oil it made me dizzy and I
vomited," she said from the hospital. "My friends carried me out and
sent me to the hospital," she said, adding that this was the 1st time
this had happened at the factory.

San Chhinh, an administrative officer at the factory, said the
workers
who fainted had recovered.

They fainted because the factory had switched the oil it used for
sewing
machines, she said, adding and that it would go back to the oil it
had
used before. "Most workers will be back on the job today," she said.

Yi Kanitha, deputy director of the occupational health department at
the
Ministry of Labour and Vocational Training, said he was unaware of
yesterday's [28 Nov 2011] fainting incident a the factory.

[Byline: Tep Nimol]

